getting-started/installation.title: Install Bittensor
getting-started/installation.description: Before you can start developing, install Bittensor and then create Bittensor wallet.

getting-started/wallets.title: Create Wallet
getting-started/wallets.description: The Bittensor wallet holds the core ownership. It is the identity technology underlying all the operations in the Bittensor network.

governance.title: Governance
governance.description: Bittensor's governance protocol transitions the management of the network from centralization within the foundation to community-ownership over time.

index.title: Welcome
index.description: Welcome! Bittensor is a protocol for decentralized subnets. Each subnet is an incentive-based competition in action. Subnets run on blockchain and constitute the core of the Bittensor ecosystem. The rewards for subnet participants are in the form of TAO tokens.

learn/anatomy-of-incentive-mechanism.title: Anatomy of Incentive Mechanism
learn/anatomy-of-incentive-mechanism.description: This section describes a conceptual “anatomy” of a subnet incentive mechanism. Read this for how to think about a subnet incentive mechanism before you begin coding it.

learn/introduction.title: Introduction
learn/introduction.description: If you are new to the Bittensor ecosystem read this section first before proceeding to participate in the Bittensor network.

reference/btcli.title: Bittensor CLI
reference/btcli.description: After you install Bittensor you can use btcli command line interface (CLI) to stake or unstake funds, run miners, check network state, and even deploy, analyze, and interface with the Bittensor network. This section presents the command and subcommand options available in btcli CLI.

senate.title: Senate
senate.description: The Senate is a group of delegates who have elected to participate in proposals, and who control a significant portion of total network stake.

subnets/register-and-participate.title: Register and Participate
subnets/register-and-participate.description: To participate either as a subnet validator or subnet miner, you must register first. Registration means registering your keys with your preferred subnet and purchasing a UID slot in that subnet.

subnets/working-with-subnets.title: Working with Subnets
subnets/working-with-subnets.description: Subnets are composed of a discrete number of UIDs. The subnet validators and subnet miners are associated with these UIDs. Each UID in the subnet belongs to a unique hotkey which in turn is connected to a unique coldkey which was used during regisration. The Yuma Consensus runs on these UIDs. This section presents a few examples showing how to work with subnets.
